05347nam a22006735i 9780822385721DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223857217 a10.1515/97808223857212doi  a(DE-B1597)553882  a(OCoLC)606310515  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF3100 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a983.06/51 aRichard, Nelly, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Insubordination of Signs :bPolitical Change, Cultural Transformation, and Poetics of the Crisis /cNelly Richard; Fredric Jameson, Stanley Fish. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (149 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin America in Translation00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAuthor's Note -- tTranslators' Acknowledgments -- tTranslators' Preface -- tNote on This Translation -- tOne. Ruptures, Memory, and Discontinuities (Homage to Walter Benjamin) -- tTwo. A Border Citation: Between Neo- and Post-Avant-Garde -- tThree. Destruction, Reconstruction, and Deconstruction -- tFour. The Social Sciences: Front Lines and Points of Retreat -- tFive. Staging Democracy and the Politics of Difference -- tSix. Conversation -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNelly Richard is one of the most prominent cultural theorists writing in Latin America today. As a participant in Chile's neo-avantgarde, Richard worked to expand the possibilities for cultural debate within the constraints imposed by the Pinochet dictatorship (1973-1990), and she has continued to offer incisive commentary about the country's transition to democracy. Well known as the founder and director of the influential journal Revista de crítica cultural, based in Santiago, Richard has been central to the dissemination throughout Latin America of work by key contemporary thinkers, including Néstor García Canclini, Jacques Derrida, Fredric Jameson, and Diamela Eltit. Her own writing provides rigorous considerations of Latin American identity, postmodernism, gender, neoliberalism, and strategies of political and cultural resistance.In The Insubordination of Signs Richard theorizes the cultural reactions-particularly within the realms of visual arts, literature, and the social sciences-to the oppression of the Chilean dictatorship. She reflects on the role of memory in the historical shadow of the military regime and on the strategies offered by marginal discourses for critiquing institutional systems of power. She considers the importance of Walter Benjamin for the theoretical self-understanding of the Latin American intellectual left, and she offers revisionary interpretations of the Chilean neo-avantgarde in terms of its relationships with the traditional left and postmodernism. Exploring the gap between Chile's new left social sciences and its "new scene" aesthetic and critical practices, Richard discusses how, with the return of democracy, the energies that had set in motion the democratizing process seemed to exhaust themselves as cultural debate was attenuated in order to reduce any risk of a return to authoritarianism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAdjustment (Psychology). 0aAuthoritarianismzChile. 0aPolitics and culturezChilexPsychological aspectsy20th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezChilexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aValdés, Adriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFish, Stanley, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBravo, Germán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJameson, Fredric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocab